members.title: Epidemic Influence Hypothesis
members.text: The outbreak of childbed fever is controlled by epidemic influences. #H1

members.title: Rough Examination Hypothesis
members.text: The outbreak of childbed fever is controlled by injuries that stem from incompetent examinations. #H2

members.title: Cadavric Substance Hypothesis
members.text: The outbreak of childbed fever is controlled by the degree of contamination with cadavric substance. #H3

members.title: Difference Between Divisions
members.text: By default, more women contract childbed fever in the First than in the Second Division of the hospital.

members.title: Washing Helps
members.text: If the students who examine the women in the First Division disinfect their hands, the ratio of women contracting childbed fever is the same in both divisions.

members.title: Death of Kolletschka
members.text: A colleague of Semmelweis suffered from symptoms similar to childbed fever and eventually died.

members.title: Birth at Home
members.text: The mortality of women who give birth at home or on their way to the hospital is significantly lower than in the First Division.

members.title: No Variations
members.text: Cases of childbed fever and corresponding mortality rates do not display spatio-temporal variations (e.g. seasonal, or from district to district) that are characteristic for epidemic diseases.
